Step 17: rk_three_density_tendsto_zero [Lean 4]
Status: [PROVED in Lean 4 — lean/RkN.lean, commit 741784c]
Claim:
  r₃(N)/N → 0 as N → ∞. More precisely, the real sequence
    f(N) = (rk 3 N : ℝ) / (N : ℝ)
  converges to 0 in the sense of Filter.Tendsto ... Filter.atTop (nhds 0).
  In Lean 4:
    theorem rk_three_density_tendsto_zero :
      Filter.Tendsto (fun N : ℕ => (rk 3 N : ℝ) / (N : ℝ)) Filter.atTop (nhds 0)
Dependencies: Step 5 (rk_three_eq_rothNumberNat);
              Mathlib: rothNumberNat_isLittleO_id
Proof:
  1. By simp_rw [rk_three_eq_rothNumberNat]: rewrite rk 3 N as rothNumberNat N.
  2. Mathlib's rothNumberNat_isLittleO_id states:
       rothNumberNat =o[atTop] id.
     I.e., rothNumberNat N / N → 0 (Roth's theorem qualitatively).
  3. Apply Asymptotics.IsLittleO.tendsto_div_nhds_zero to extract the Tendsto form.
  Complete Lean proof:
    simp_rw [rk_three_eq_rothNumberNat]
    exact rothNumberNat_isLittleO_id.tendsto_div_nhds_zero

  MATHEMATICAL CONTENT (Roth's theorem):
    This is the qualitative version of Roth's 1953 theorem: any subset of {1,...,N}
    with density ≥ ε (for any fixed ε > 0) contains a 3-AP for large enough N.
    Equivalently, r₃(N)/N → 0. Proved in Mathlib via Szemerédi's regularity lemma
    (or corners theorem; see Mathlib.Combinatorics.Additive.Corner.Roth).
    Note: The quantitative rate (1/log log N, (log N)^{1/9}, (log N)^{1/6}/log log N)
    is NOT in Mathlib; only the qualitative o(1) statement is available.
QED.

