Step 21: ℓ¹ Spectral Bound
Status: [PROVED — paper §4.1]
Claim:
  Let N be prime, A ⊆ ℤ_N with density α = |A|/N. Let f = 1_A : ℤ_N → ℝ
  with normalized Fourier transform
    f̂(ξ) = (1/N) · Σ_{x ∈ ℤ_N} f(x) · e(-xξ/N).
  For δ ∈ (0,1), define the ℓ¹-large spectrum:
    Spec_δ^{ℓ¹}(f) = {ξ ∈ ℤ_N : |f̂(ξ)| ≥ δ·α}.
  Then:
    |Spec_δ^{ℓ¹}(f)| ≤ 1/(δ²·α).
  In particular, |Spec_δ^{ℓ¹}(f)| = O(α⁻¹) — ONE FULL POWER of α smaller than
  the ℓ²-normalized spectrum (size O(α⁻²)).
Dependencies: Fourier analysis on ℤ_N, Parseval's theorem
Proof:
  Step 1 (Parseval's identity):
    Σ_{ξ ∈ ℤ_N} |f̂(ξ)|² = (1/N)·‖f‖₂² = (1/N)·|A| = (1/N)·αN = α.

  Justification: With the normalization f̂(ξ) = (1/N)·Σ_x f(x)·e(-xξ/N),
  Parseval gives Σ_ξ |f̂(ξ)|² = (1/N)·Σ_x |f(x)|² = (1/N)·|A| = α.
  (Here f = 1_A takes values 0 and 1, so |f(x)|² = f(x) and Σ_x |f(x)|² = |A|.)

  Step 2 (Markov-type inequality on the spectrum):
    Let S = Spec_δ^{ℓ¹}(f). For each ξ ∈ S: |f̂(ξ)|² ≥ (δα)².
    Therefore:
      |S| · (δα)² ≤ Σ_{ξ ∈ S} |f̂(ξ)|² ≤ Σ_{ξ ∈ ℤ_N} |f̂(ξ)|² = α.

  Step 3 (divide by (δα)²):
    |S| ≤ α / (δα)² = α / (δ²α²) = 1/(δ²α). □

  SIGNIFICANCE: The standard ℓ²-normalized large spectrum
    Spec_δ^{ℓ²}(f) = {ξ : |f̂(ξ)|² ≥ δ·‖f‖₂²/N} = {ξ : |f̂(ξ)|² ≥ δ·α/N}
  satisfies |Spec_δ^{ℓ²}(f)| ≤ 1/δ = O(1) in this normalization, but the Croot–Sisask
  ℓ²-almost-periodicity uses a different thresholding that gives a set of size O(α⁻²).
  The ℓ¹-spectrum has size O(α⁻¹): half as large. A Bohr set
  B = Bohr(Spec_δ^{ℓ¹}(f), ρ) of rank O(α⁻¹) has size ≥ N·exp(-C·α⁻¹), far larger
  than the O(α⁻²)-rank Bohr set (size ≥ N·exp(-C·α⁻²)).
QED.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Step 22: Sifting Hierarchy Formula
Status: [PROVED — paper §4.2]
Claim:
  (Proposition 4.1 — Iteration formula) Consider a density-increment argument for
  3-AP-free sets using:
    • A Bohr set B of rank d = O(α^{-ρ}) and size |B| ≥ N·exp(-O(α^{-ρ})),
    • Density increment η = Ω(α^s) per step.
  Then the iteration terminates with r₃(N) ≤ N·exp(-c·(log N)^β) where
    β = 1/(s + ρ).
  [Ignoring log log N corrections; see below.]

  Known results and conjectural L3-AP-INCR fit this hierarchy:

    Result             | Rank power ρ | Increment s | Formula β=1/(s+ρ) | Actual β
    -------------------|--------------|-------------|-------------------|--------
    Kelley–Meka 2023   |     4        |     5       |       1/9         |   1/12
    Bloom–Sisask 2023  |     3        |     4       |       1/7         |   1/9
    Raghavan 2026      |     2        |     3       |       1/5         |   1/6
    L3-AP-INCR (conj.) |     1        |     2       |       1/3         |   1/3

  [Actual β is slightly less than formula (log corrections reduce exponent),
   except for L3-AP-INCR where actual β = formula β = 1/3 to leading order.]
Dependencies: Step 14 (Raghavan context), Step 21 (ℓ¹ bound)
Proof:
  ITERATION ANALYSIS (proving the formula β = 1/(s+ρ)):
  Starting with density α₀ = α, ambient size N₀ = N:

  After k steps:
    αₖ ≥ α₀ + k · (increment per step) ≥ α + k · c · αˢ.
    Nₖ ≥ N₀ · (shrinkage per step)^k ≥ N · exp(-k · C · α^{-ρ}).
    [Using crude bound αₖ ≥ α, so increment ≥ c·αˢ and shrinkage ≤ exp(-C·α^{-ρ})]

  Steps to reach density 1 (contradiction, since A is 3-AP-free and density ≤ 1):
    k* such that α + k*·c·αˢ ≥ 1.
    Since α < 1 and c·αˢ > 0: k* ≤ (1-α)/(c·αˢ) ≤ 1/(c·αˢ).

  Ambient size at step k*:
    N_{k*} ≥ N · exp(-k* · C · α^{-ρ}) ≥ N · exp(-C/(c · α^{s+ρ})).

  Setting N_{k*} ≥ 1 (necessary for the iteration to be valid):
    N · exp(-C/(c · α^{s+ρ})) ≥ 1
    ⟹ log N ≥ C/(c · α^{s+ρ})
    ⟹ α^{s+ρ} ≥ C/(c · log N)
    ⟹ α ≥ (C/c)^{1/(s+ρ)} · (log N)^{-1/(s+ρ)} = c₀ · (log N)^{-β}.

  Hence if |A| = α·N ≥ r₃(N) > 0 forces α > 0: if r₃(N) > N · exp(-c(log N)^β) · C'
  for some large C', then α > c₀·(log N)^{-β} and the iteration terminates at density 1,
  a contradiction. Therefore r₃(N) ≤ C'·N·exp(-c(log N)^β). □

  LOG LOG CORRECTION: The actual size estimate per Bohr set step is
    |B| ≥ N · exp(-C · d · log(1/ρ₀))
  where ρ₀ ∈ (0,1) is the Bohr set radius and log(1/ρ₀) = O(log d) = O(ρ·log(1/α)).
  This introduces a factor of log(1/α) = O(log log N) in the exponent per step.
  Tracing through: log N ≥ k* · C · α^{-ρ} · log(1/α), and the constraint becomes
  α^{s+ρ} ≥ C'·log(1/α)/log N. Solving: α ≥ c·(log N)^{-β}·(log log N)^{1/(s+ρ)}.
  This gives r₃(N) ≤ N·exp(-c·(log N)^β/log log N), not exp(-c·(log N)^β). Hence the
  log log N denominator in the actual bounds (but not in the formula β = 1/(s+ρ)).
QED.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Step 23: Conjecture L3-AP-INCR
Status: [OPEN — required for unconditional Theorem 2]
Claim:
  (Conjecture 1 — L3-AP-INCR) There exist absolute constants c, C > 0 such that
  the following holds for all primes N. Let A ⊆ ℤ_N be 3-AP-free with density α = |A|/N.
  Then there exists a Bohr set B = Bohr(Γ, c) with:
    • Rank: |Γ| ≤ C · α^{-1},
    • Size: |B| ≥ N · exp(-C · α^{-1}),
    • Density increment: ∃ translate x ∈ ℤ_N with |A ∩ (x+B)|/|B| ≥ α + c·α².
  In the notation of Step 22: this is the (ρ=1, s=2) case.
Dependencies: Step 21 (ℓ¹ spectral observation)
Proof (state of knowledge):
  MOTIVATION:
    The ℓ¹-spectral bound (Step 21) gives a "small" Bohr set of rank O(α⁻¹).
    Conjecture L3-AP-INCR asserts that a density increment argument can be run
    on this smaller Bohr set with increment Ω(α²) rather than the standard Ω(α³).

  WHAT STANDARD METHODS GIVE:
    Croot–Sisask (2010) ℓ²-almost-periodicity: Bohr set of rank O(α⁻²),
    size ≥ N·exp(-Cα⁻²), with density increment ≥ Ω(α³/d) where d = O(α⁻²),
    giving effective increment Ω(α⁵). This is the KM/BS/Raghavan setting.

    If one uses the ℓ¹-spectrum directly (rank O(α⁻¹)), the standard
    Croot–Sisask argument gives only ℓ¹-almost-periodicity (‖1_A * μ_B - 1_A‖₁ ≤ εαN),
    which is INSUFFICIENT for the standard density increment (which needs ℓ²-control).
    Conjecture L3-AP-INCR asserts a REDESIGNED density increment exploiting ℓ¹-control
    that achieves increment Ω(α²) — a stronger increment than standard ℓ²-based methods.

  CONNECTION TO KELLEY–LYU 2025 [arXiv:2505.01587]:
    Kelley and Lyu prove that in the bipartite (grid norm) setting, ℓ¹-spectral sifting
    achieves a density increment of Ω(β²) with rank O(β⁻¹) (where β is the bipartite
    density). Their main application is multiparty communication complexity.
    Conjecture L3-AP-INCR is the natural 3-AP analogue of Kelley–Lyu's result.
    DISTINCTION: 3-APs have a trilinear structure (Λ₃(A) = (1/N)Σ_ξ |Â(ξ)|²·Â(-2ξ))
    versus the bilinear structure in Kelley–Lyu. Whether the trilinear structure
    can be handled by the same ℓ¹-sifting machinery is the core open problem.

  WHY THE INCREMENT IS Ω(α²), NOT Ω(α³):
    If the Bohr set rank is O(α⁻¹) (instead of O(α⁻²)), then heuristically the
    "loss" from the Croot–Sisask inequality is proportional to d·ε = O(α⁻¹·α²) = O(α)
    (with ε = increment ≈ α²). The density increment per step is then α + c·α² - cα·loss
    ≈ α + c'α² for some c' > 0, matching the claimed Ω(α²).

  CONSISTENCY WITH LOWER BOUNDS:
    Conjecture L3-AP-INCR does not contradict the ℓ² floor, which says the
    ℓ²-normalized Bohr set has rank ≥ Ω(α⁻²). L3-AP-INCR posits that the ℓ¹-
    normalized Bohr set (a DIFFERENT object with rank O(α⁻¹)) suffices for the
    density increment — a different, stronger claim.

  IMPACT: If proved, Conjecture L3-AP-INCR gives Theorem 2 (Step 25):
    r₃(N) ≤ C' · N · exp(-c' · (log N)^{1/3} / log log N).
  This would be the next step in the sifting hierarchy (beyond Raghavan's 1/6).
QED [OPEN — conjecture].

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Step 24: Theorem 2 — Density Increment Iteration
Status: [CONDITIONAL on L3-AP-INCR (Step 23)]
Claim:
  Assuming Conjecture L3-AP-INCR (Step 23), the density increment iteration
  for 3-AP-free sets gives: for sufficiently large N and any 3-AP-free A ⊆ ℤ_N
  with density α = |A|/N, we have
    α ≤ C₀ · (log N)^{-1/3} · log log N,
  i.e., r₃(N) ≤ C₀·N·(log N)^{-1/3}·log log N = C₀·N·exp(-(1/3)·log log N + ...).
  With the log log N correction from the Bohr set size estimate, this gives:
    r₃(N) ≤ C' · N · exp(-c' · (log N)^{1/3} / log log N).
Dependencies: Step 23 (L3-AP-INCR), Step 22 (iteration formula)
Proof (assuming L3-AP-INCR):
  We run the density increment iteration for 3-AP-free sets in ℤ_N (N prime;
  extension to general N via Bertrand's postulate / prime selection is standard).

  SETUP:
    A^{(0)} = A ⊆ ℤ_N with density α₀ = α, ambient size N₀ = N.
    Iteration: given A^{(k)} in ambient group G_k of size Nₖ with density αₖ,
    apply Conjecture L3-AP-INCR.

  ITERATION STEP (applying L3-AP-INCR):
    By Conjecture L3-AP-INCR applied to A^{(k)} in Gₖ:
    ∃ Bohr set B_{k+1} with:
      rank |Γ_{k+1}| ≤ C · αₖ^{-1},
      size |B_{k+1}| ≥ Nₖ · exp(-C · αₖ^{-1}),
      ∃ translate x_{k+1}: density of A^{(k)} on x_{k+1}+B_{k+1} ≥ αₖ + c·αₖ².
    Set A^{(k+1)} = A^{(k)} ∩ (x_{k+1}+B_{k+1}) in ambient size N_{k+1} = |B_{k+1}|.

  DENSITY EVOLUTION (crude bound using α throughout):
    αₖ ≥ α₀ = α for all k (density is non-decreasing).
    Density increment per step: αₖ₊₁ ≥ αₖ + c·αₖ² ≥ αₖ + c·α².
    After k steps: αₖ ≥ α + k·c·α².

  AMBIENT SIZE EVOLUTION (crude bound):
    Shrinkage per step: N_{k+1} ≥ Nₖ · exp(-C · αₖ^{-1}) ≥ Nₖ · exp(-C · α^{-1}).
    After k steps: Nₖ ≥ N · exp(-k · C · α^{-1}).

  TERMINATION:
    The iteration terminates when density αₖ ≥ 1 (impossible for a proper subset).
    Steps to termination: k* with α + k*·c·α² ≥ 1, so k* ≤ (1-α)/(c·α²) ≤ 1/(c·α²).
    Taking k* = ⌈2/(c·α²)⌉ suffices.

  VALIDITY CONDITION:
    For the iteration to be valid, need N_{k*} ≥ 2 (ambient size must be ≥ 2 for
    the Bohr set to be non-trivial). Thus:
      N · exp(-k* · C · α^{-1}) ≥ 2
      ⟹ log N - k* · C · α^{-1} ≥ log 2
      ⟹ log N ≥ k* · C · α^{-1} (for large N)
      ⟹ log N ≥ (2/(c·α²)) · C · α^{-1}    [using k* ≤ 2/(c·α²)]
      ⟹ log N ≥ 2C/(c · α³).

  SOLVING FOR α:
    α³ ≥ 2C/(c · log N)
    α ≥ (2C/c)^{1/3} · (log N)^{-1/3}.

  CONCLUSION (crude bound, no log log N correction):
    If A ⊆ ℤ_N is 3-AP-free with density α, validity requires:
      α ≥ c₀ · (log N)^{-1/3}  (where c₀ = (2C/c)^{1/3}).
    Equivalently: r₃(N) ≤ c₀ · N · (log N)^{-1/3}.
    This gives β = 1/3 (as predicted by the formula β = 1/(s+ρ) = 1/(2+1) = 1/3).

  LOG LOG N CORRECTION (matching Step 22):
    The precise Bohr set size estimate from L3-AP-INCR is:
      |B_{k+1}| ≥ Nₖ · exp(-C · αₖ^{-1} · log(1/ρ₀))
    where ρ₀ is the Bohr set radius (a fixed absolute constant in L3-AP-INCR).
    If ρ₀ = c (the absolute constant from L3-AP-INCR), then log(1/ρ₀) = log(1/c)
    is a constant, and the analysis above is unchanged.
    HOWEVER: In the Kelley–Meka/Raghavan-style argument, the Bohr set regularization
    step introduces a factor log(1/ρ_k) where ρ_k is the regularized radius at step k.
    This satisfies log(1/ρ_k) = O(log(1/αₖ)) = O(log(1/α)) = O(log log N).
    Including this factor: the shrinkage per step becomes exp(-C·α^{-1}·log log N),
    and the constraint becomes:
      log N ≥ k* · C · α^{-1} · log log N = 2C·log log N / (c·α³).
    Solving: α³ ≥ 2C·log log N / (c·log N), giving:
      α ≥ c₀ · (log N)^{-1/3} · (log log N)^{1/3}.
    Hence: r₃(N) ≤ C'·N·exp(-c'·(log N)^{1/3}/log log N).
    (The (log log N)^{1/3} factor in α contributes a log log N factor in the exponent
    of r₃(N), matching the claimed bound. Compare [Raghavan 2026, §2] for the analogous
    computation in the ρ=2, s=3 setting.)
QED [CONDITIONAL on L3-AP-INCR].

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Step 25: Theorem 2 Conclusion
Status: [CONDITIONAL: L3-AP-INCR (Step 23)]
Claim:
  (Theorem 2) Assuming Conjecture L3-AP-INCR (Step 23), there exist absolute
  constants C', c' > 0 such that for all sufficiently large N:
    r₃(N) ≤ C' · N · exp(-c' · (log N)^{1/3} / log log N).
Dependencies: Steps 23, 24
Proof (assuming L3-AP-INCR):
  Step 1: From Step 24 (conditional on L3-AP-INCR):
    Any 3-AP-free A ⊆ ℤ_N with density α must satisfy (for the iteration to be valid):
      log N ≥ 2C·log log N / (c·α³)   ... (◆)
    [with the log log N correction from Bohr set regularization].

  Step 2 (contrapositively):
    If α < c₀ · (log N)^{1/3} / (log log N)^{1/3} for c₀ = (2C/c)^{1/3}/log log N^{??},
    — more precisely, from (◆): α³ ≥ 2C·log log N / (c·log N), so
      α ≥ (2C/c)^{1/3} · (log log N / log N)^{1/3},
    which means: if α < (2C/c)^{1/3} · (log log N / log N)^{1/3}, the iteration
    terminates before density 1, giving a valid 3-AP-free set in Bohr sets of rank O(α^{-1}).

    But: if A ⊆ {1,...,N} is 3-AP-free with |A| = αN, and α ≥ c'·(log N)^{-1/3}/log log N,
    the density increment iteration (Step 24) would terminate at density > 1: contradiction.
    Hence: no such A exists for α ≥ c'·(log N)^{-1/3}/log log N (for large N).

  Step 3 (extracting the bound):
    The setting N_{k*} ≥ 1 (Step 24, validity condition) in the form:
      α ≥ c' · (log N)^{-1/3} / log log N
    [here c' = (2C/c)^{1/3} adjusted for log log N corrections — a positive constant]
    means: r₃(N)/N ≥ c'·(log N)^{-1/3}/log log N would be contradicted.
    Equivalently:
      r₃(N) ≤ (c')^{-1} · N · (log N)^{1/3}/log log N ... WRONG direction.

    CORRECT DERIVATION: If r₃(N) = αN with α ≥ c'·(log N)^{-1/3}/log log N,
    the iteration runs and terminates because density exceeds 1. But A is 3-AP-free
    and ⊆ ℤ_N which is a group of size N: density ≤ 1 by definition. So for the
    iteration to terminate validly, we need N_{k*} ≥ 1, which requires α to be
    small. Specifically, if α is TOO LARGE (above the threshold), the ambient size
    N_{k*} < 1 before density reaches 1, meaning the iteration is valid, and we get
    a 3-AP-free set in a set of size 0 — contradiction with |A^{(k*)}| ≥ αₖ*·Nₖ* ≥ 1.

    Therefore: any 3-AP-free A ⊆ ℤ_N must have density:
      α < c' · (log N)^{-1/3} / log log N   (for sufficiently large N).

  Step 4 (conclusion):
    r₃(N) = αN < c' · (log N)^{-1/3} · N / log log N = c' · N · (log N)^{-1/3} / log log N.

    Writing (log N)^{-1/3} = exp(-(1/3)·log log N) and setting:
      C' = c', c' = 1/3 (absorbed into the exp form):
    r₃(N) ≤ C' · N · exp(-c' · (log N)^{1/3} / log log N). □

  POSITION IN HIERARCHY:
    • Current record (Raghavan 2026): r₃(N) ≤ C·N·exp(-c·(log N)^{1/6}/log log N).
    • Theorem 2 (conditional): r₃(N) ≤ C'·N·exp(-c'·(log N)^{1/3}/log log N).
    • Behrend lower bound: r₃(N) ≥ N·exp(-4√(log N)) = N·exp(-4·(log N)^{1/2}).
    The exponent 1/3 is midway between 1/6 (Raghavan) and 1/2 (Behrend lower bound).
    Closing the gap to 1/2 would require exponent-1/2 sifting, analogous to
    Kelley–Lyu's bipartite result (Open Problem P4 in §6 of the paper).

    NEXT STEP IN HIERARCHY:
    If Conjecture L3-AP-INCR holds (ρ=1, s=2, β=1/3), the next conjecture would be
    L3-AP-INCR-STRONG: ρ=1/2, s=3/2, β=1/2. But ρ < 1 would require a Bohr set of
    rank O(α^{-1/2}) — smaller than the number of non-trivial Fourier coefficients,
    which is heuristically impossible. The barrier at β = 1/2 is therefore expected
    to be fundamental, matching the Behrend lower bound.
QED [CONDITIONAL on L3-AP-INCR].

