Step 31: Refined Conjecture 2 (RC2) — Three-Route Analysis
Status: [OPEN — stronger than C2; lovász13 structural analysis June 2026]
Claim:
  (Refined Conjecture 2 / RC2) For every 4-AP-free A ⊆ {1,...,N} with |A| = M ≥ 2,
  there exists d ∈ S = {d : |A_d| ≥ M²/(4N)} satisfying ALL three of:
    (i)   |A_d| ≥ M²/(4N)        [popular — automatic by d ∈ S]
    (ii)  T₃(A_d) = 0            [fully 3-AP-free = G(d) = 0]
    (iii) |A_d| ≤ (1/4) · max_{d' ∈ S} |A_{d'}|   [lower-quarter size]
  RC2 implies C2 (Gap 3.1, Step 12); C2 implies Theorem 1 (Steps 13–15).
  Threshold 1/4: per-trial min wfrac = |A_d|/maxpop always ≤ 0.25 (mean 0.21,
  range [0.17, 0.25]) across 200 trials at N=600,700 (commit 7412f2e). Witnesses
  are abundant: ~119 per trial (not needle-in-haystack). argmax fiber (wfrac=1)
  never 3-AP-free for N≥120 (comp4, commit 02f6cd2).

Dependencies: Steps 9–12, 27–29; lovász11 D(x,e) lemma (commit 31566bc)

Analysis (lovász13, 2026-06-21):

  ROUTE A (Fourier / Bohr sets for small fibers):
  Lemma A.2: T₃(A_d) ≤ |A_d|² · β(A_d), where β(A_d) = max_{ξ≠0}|Â_d(ξ)|/|A_d|.
  For T₃(A_d) = 0, we need β(A_d) < |A_d|^{-2}; this requires extreme Fourier
  cancellation in the triple sum Σ_ξ Â_d(ξ)²Â_d(-2ξ), not merely small |Â_d(ξ)|.
  Main Gap A.1: 4-AP-freeness of A does not force Fourier cancellation in A_d.
  Good fibers have HIGHER Fourier bias than bad fibers (commit b5827d9): they are
  small/sparse sets with few cancellations. The smallness of |A_d| does not help.
  Main Gap A.2: Bohr structure of A does not transfer to A_d = A ∩ (A-d).
  Estimate: 3–10 years for a Fourier proof (requires new fiber-cancellation lemma).

  ROUTE B (Counting argument from bad_frac bound):
  D(x,e) lemma (Step 29 / lovász11): Σ_{d∈S} T₃(A_d) ≤ T₃(A)·r₄(N).
  Bounding bad_frac = |S_bad|/|S|: since each bad d has T₃(A_d) ≥ 1,
    |S_bad| ≤ Σ_{d∈S_bad} T₃(A_d) ≤ T₃(A)·r₄(N).
  For bad_frac < 1 we need T₃(A)·r₄(N) < |S|. But T₃(A)·r₄(N) ≫ |S| generically
  (T₃(A) ≈ α²N² and r₄(N) ≈ M, while |S| ≤ N), so D(x,e) bound cannot force
  bad_frac < 1 alone.
  Conditional result (Theorem B.5): RC2 holds assuming:
    H1: bad_frac(A) ≤ 1 - c₀ for some universal c₀ > 0 (some popular fibers good)
    H2: every d ∈ S with |A_d| > maxpop/4 satisfies T₃(A_d) > 0 (large fibers bad)
  Neither H1 nor H2 is proved. H1 implies C2 (strictly stronger than C2).
  Key question: does bad_frac ≤ 1 - c follow from a theorem for all 4-AP-free A?
  Estimate: 3–10 years (would require proving H1, which is at least as hard as C2).

  ROUTE C (Structural — argmax fiber is bad):
  Trivial special case (Theorem C.7): If A is itself 3-AP-free, every fiber A_d ⊆ A
  is 3-AP-free by heredity → C2 trivially holds (all popular fibers are good).
  Density heuristic: argmax fiber has |A_{d*}| = maxpop ≥ M²/(4N). For a random
  set B of size s, T₃(B) ≈ s³/N. For s = maxpop ≈ M²/(4N):
    T₃(argmax) ≈ M^6/(64N^4).
  For T₃ < 1 we need M < 2N^{2/3}. But r₄(N) ≥ N·exp(-C√logN) ≫ N^{2/3}.
  Hence T₃(argmax) ≫ 1 for optimal 4-AP-free sets — consistent with 0% argmax T₃=0
  for N≥120, but NOT proved (A_d is not a random set).
  Main Gap C.1: Cannot prove T₃(A_{d*}) > 0 without either (a) maxpop > r₃(N)
  (equivalent to C2 holding → circular) or (b) a direct 2×3 grid in A with column d*.
  Estimate: 3–10 years to prove argmax-is-bad; open for decades for full C2.

  MOST PROMISING TARGET:
  Prove H2: for every 4-AP-free A and every d ∈ S with |A_d| > maxpop/4,
  T₃(A_d) > 0 (large popular fibers always contain 3-APs).
  This is a single-fiber statement amenable to density+Roth arguments:
  if |A_d| > maxpop/4 ≥ M²/(16N), is |A_d| large enough to force a 3-AP?
  By Roth: 3-APs forced iff |A_d| > r₃(N). Current gap: M²/(16N) < r₃(N) in
  general (since M ≤ r₄(N) and r₄(N)² ≤ 4N·r₃(N) conditioned on C2).
  The gap closes if M² ≫ 16N·r₃(N), i.e., C2 itself forces the argmax to be bad —
  another circular route. New ideas needed.

  ADDITIONAL STRUCTURAL RESULT (from Bonus Task 1):
  If all good fibers have wfrac > ε, the van Corput bound worsens:
    r₄(N) ≤ 2·(1/√ε)·√(N·r₃(N)).
  Conversely, RC2 (witnesses with wfrac ≤ 1/4) gives the same constant as C2.
  The 3-AP-free gap structure: if no good fiber exists in [threshold, ε·maxpop],
  then small popular fibers are all bad — a "3-AP-free gap" property of 4-AP-free sets,
  not seen empirically and likely false.

  BAD_FRAC BOUND STATUS (Bonus Task 2):
  The good-fiber fraction bound is purely empirical and falls below 10% in worst-case trials at N≥3000 (commit 4908ff5). C2 (existence) still holds but quantitative ≥10% bound is disproved.
  No theorem currently forces bad_frac ≤ 1 - c for any c > 0.
  The averaging bound from D(x,e) requires T₃(A)·r₄(N) < |S|, which fails generically.
  Proving Conjectured Lemma B.6 (bad_frac ≤ 1-c) would imply C2 and is strictly harder.

Computational evidence: 0 RC2 counterexamples in 4893+ trials N≤200000; per-trial
  min_wfrac always ≤ 0.25 (mean ~0.200, stable through N=200000; N=50000 AND N=100000 avg=0.2000=1/5 exactly); 1871 witnesses/trial at
  N=200000 (avg ~0.200 across N=2500-200000, stable; threshold converging to 1/5; commits 4908ff5, fb986eb, 11b53b9, a0821da, 77d7383, 4d6e11d; Δ=+0.003/50k at large N; asymptote 0.993-0.997). Argmax T₃=0 rate: 0% for N≥120 (comp4 data, commit 02f6cd2).
Theoretical analysis of the 1/5 threshold: see Appendix B of submittable_proof.md
  (analysis source: research/wit_1fifth_analysis.md, commit 3facd5f). Core result:
  avg_min_wfrac ≈ L/P where L=M²/(4N) is the popularity threshold and P=maxpop;
  both L and P scale as N^0.40, so P/L≈5.1±0.1 is scale-invariant, giving
  min_wfrac≈1/5. Poisson model: T₃(A_s)≈Poisson(s³/N) → probability of 3AP-free
  decays superexponentially above L (e^{-150}≈10^{-65} at s=P). Most tractable
  proof route: establish energy bound E(A)≤C_E·M³/N for 4AP-free A (status: open;
  would imply P/L≤8C_E≈5 → min_wfrac≥1/5 → RC2 unconditionally).

QED [OPEN — empirically robust; three routes each hit genuine obstacles; conditional
  on H1+H2 (Theorem B.5); probability estimates: Route A 3–10yr; Route B 3–10yr;
  Route C argmax result 3–10yr, full C2 open for decades].

